  <title>Modelling community small water supply system</title>
  <description type="1">The project will be implemented in Mecanhelas district, Niassa province, Northern of Mozambique. The proposed intervention aims to improve the living conditions of vulnerable people with access to safe drinking water by modelling a small community managed sustainable solar pump water supply system with solar panels that will directly benefit 7,602 people from 4 rural communities and indirectly around 350-380 people who live in the neighbouring villages.  The model will be promoted at district, provincial and national level. Water Committees will be formed in each of the 4 target rural locations and 48 members will be trained to manage and maintain the system. In addition to water access, 487 school children studying at the primary school will benefit from safe sanitation facilities through the construction of inclusive sanitary blocks (toilets and handwashing facilities). A school health club will be formed who will raise awareness among their peers on good hygiene practices and menstrual hygiene management. Effective hygiene messages will be delivered, through a trained network of key agents, such as community members, leaders and midwives, with the latter educating women and families on Healthy start of children under five. Hygiene education will be delivered among communities on the issues of good hygiene and sanitation practices.</description>
